 suggested carbon was assimilated mostly from the seagrass Posidonia spp., the dune grass Spinifex longifolia and red algae for amphipods and from brown algae, red algae and dune vegetation for dipteran flies. We conclude that the presence of marine-derived wrack plays a major role in subsidising production of macroinvertebrates on beaches of south-western Australia. We suggest that marine subsidies can play a role in supporting terrestrial production, even in oligotrophic marine environments. {\textcopyright} 2007 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
author = {Ince, R and Hyndes, G A and Lavery, P S and Vanderklift, M A},
doi = {10.1016/j.ecss.2007.03.029},
file = {:C$\backslash$:/Users/Hp/Documents/Journal library/Ince{\_}2007.pdf:pdf},
