@article{Koop1982,
abstract = {Primary decomposition of intertidally stranded kelp Ecklonia maxima in a mixed substrate microcosm is effected by bacteria rather than by fungi. Initial colonisation by cocci to lysis and release of cell contents. Lysed cells are then colonised by bacterial rods. High concentrations of leachates, reaching 5,640 mg carbon1 super(-1) subsequently appear beneath the decomposing kelp. Over 90{\%} of the carbon in these leachates is utilised by bacteria during drainage through a strip of sand 1 m long, 50 cm wide and 12 cm deep, although on an open beach other organisms, e. g. nematodes, may be capable of direct absorption of such organic matter. Calculation of carbon flow via grazing invertebrates and through bacteria shows that 23-27{\%} of the carbon in kelp is converted to bacterial carbon. Estimates of the bacterial carbon in equilibrium with the kelp cast up on the strandline suggest that 1648 g of kelp carbon is deposited per metre of strandline each 8 d.},
annote = {{\textgreater} This paper summarises the results of studies made on the realtive rate of utilisation of kelp by the dominant consumers and by microheterotrophic decomposer organisms. The results allowed us to make some quantitative estimates of the relative significance of consumer organisms and microheterotrophic pathways in the energetics of the sandy beach community. Stydy site was located at Kommetjie. Sampling included invertebrate consumer species, microbial communities and biochemical components.

{\textgreater} The results presented in this study suggest that bacteria are primarily responsible for the decomposistion and subsequent utilisation of kelp debris on the strandline, rather than fungi as generlly reported. Succession of microbial communities was also clear.

{\textgreater} Lysis of the cells, most likely through bacterial decomposition, results in the release of high concentrations of dissolved organic matter as leachates immediatey below decomposing kelp. Values as high as 5640 mg carbon l(-1) was recorded. The high concentrations of such compounds may result in the direct absorption by eiofauna which occurs under natural conditions in more mature sand columns on sandy open beaches.

{\textgreater} In the microcosom study, it was found that of 100 grams carbon in kelp 8.9{\%} was consumed by invertebrates.
{\textgreater}Grazers consumed {\~{}}6.9{\%} of orginal kelp carbon
{\textgreater} Broader study showed that 74{\%} of bech-cast kelp is consumed by the amphipod Talorchestia capensis and the diperan larvae Fucellia capensis, and the dipteran larva of Fucellia capensis.

{\textgreater} Carbon flow analyses of both decomposer and consumer dominated systems suggest that some 23 -27{\%} of the carbon from kelp is assimilated into large standing stock of bacterial carbon in the intertidal zone whilst the residual 73 to 77{\%} of the carbon from kelp is rapidly mineralised by the sand beach bacteria within {\~{}}8 days. This microbrial action is similar to what has been reported for water comlumns and therefore microbial communities play a central role in the rapid regeneration of inorganic materials needed to support the high primary production of a kelp bed.
},
